text.tspan: A constructive approach for graphs with long range dependencies
University of Freiburg, Georges-Koehler-Allee 106, D-79110 Freiburg, Germany
Method: GraSCoS Graph Substitution Constructive System

flowRoot.flowPara: Graph data structures allow us to model complex entities in a natural and expressive way. In the literature, several types of discriminative systems that can deal with graphs in input are known (e.g. recursive neural networks, graph kernels, etc), however, there are few genera-tive or constructive approaches that can output graphs belonging with high probability to a desired distribution or class.
Model quality assessment in learnable design problems
In classification problems it is easy to compare the predicted class to the available true class.
But with newly designed instances we do not have true class assignments (impossible or expensive to resort to oracle).
Simple yet effective strategy:
transform the performance evaluation into a classification evaluation problem
Transformation:
- induce the generative model and produce candidates for both positive and neg class
- train a binary classifier only on newly designed candidates
- compute the predictive performance on a test set of known instances
- compare to the performance obtained by the same type of discriminative learner when trained on the original set
If the newly constructed instances belong to the same concept class, then both models should perform equally well on the same test set.
Characteristics: context-sensitive, robust to outliers and computationally efficient (linear time complexity in both the model induction and the candidate generation phase).
The key notion is substitutability: all substrings that always occur in the same context (i.e. that are congruent) belong to the same implicit category and can therefore be substituted.
We extend this notion in two ways: 1) we upgrade it from strings to graphs; and 2) we allow a local notion of context.
Substitutable graphs are neighborhood subgraphs (i.e. graphs induced by a root vertex v and all vertices that are within distance R from v).
Interface is the difference between two co-rooted neighborhood subgraphs of different radii.
Thickness T, is half of the difference of the two radii.
Core is the inner co-rooted neighborhood graph of radius R.
The model induction phase:
- enumerate all possible cores and their correspondent interfaces.
- train a robust and fast graph kernel SVM discriminative model (stochastic gradient descent SVM with NSPDK) on binary classification problem.
The construction of candidate graphs phase:
- iterate substitution of congruent cores
(i.e. cores with matching interface).
- score resulting graphs with SVM.
Given a concept as a (finite) set of instances...
- standard task for ML:
does instance z belong to concept C?
classification or regression
- a more challenging task:
output instance z that belongs to concept C!
constructive, generative
Interesting applications when z is structured:
- design molecules with desired bio-activity
- design bacterial metabolic networks to obtain higher yields
- design rules of games to engage specific type of users
- design controllers for complex robotic tasks
- design policies for complex reinforcement learning tasks
How to guarantee that instances to score are feasible?
How to move on the manifold?
How to derive the constraints that guarantee the feasibility of the graphs from data?
We call it: learnable design problem
Links to the configuration problems in constraint programming
Links to graph-grammars (algebraic approach double-pushout)
Upgrade to implicit constraints and prefereces:
Grammar rules (daughter subgraphs to substitute, the embedding rule) are induced from data;
Preference score for whole graph is induced from data;
The user needs only to develop a suitable data representation encoding and provide a set of examples.
References:
Zellig S. Harris, Distributional structure, Word, 1954
A Clark and R Eyraud, Polynomial identification in the limit of substitutable context-free languages, Journal of Machine Learning Research, 2007
Costa, F., De Grave, K. Fast neighborhood subgraph pairwise distance kernel. ICML, 2010
Dataset: 4K molecular graphs ( 25 vertices x mol)
Concept: toxicity (balanced dataset)
Induction:
Runtime for model induction: linear (0.7 sec / graph) (can be trivially parallelized!)
Growth of grammar: linear (# interfaces 15xN, # cores 3xN)
Production:
Num substitutions per molecule: 50, 90, 7000 (core radius 0, 1, 2)
Runtime for candidate generation: linear (20 graphs / sec)
Num mol in test set exactly re-constructed 26/700 (4%)
